TY  - JOUR
T1  - R&D Cooperation Between Firms—A Perceived Transaction Cost Perspective
AU  - Brockhoff, Klaus
Y1  - 1992/04/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.38.4.514
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.38.4.514
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 514
EP  - 524
VL  - 38
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Transaction cost is considered as an explanatory variable for the choice between markets and various organizational arrangements for performing some predefined tasks, such as engaging in private R&D. With respect to R&D cooperation between firms, we show that the perception of high transaction cost is related to certain characteristics of the firm and to the type of R&D task. We also show a relationship between the perception of transaction cost and the perceived success of the cooperation. The analysis sheds light on various determinants of transaction costs.
AB  - Transaction cost is considered as an explanatory variable for the choice between markets and various organizational arrangements for performing some predefined tasks, such as engaging in private R&D. With respect to R&D cooperation between firms, we show that the perception of high transaction cost is related to certain characteristics of the firm and to the type of R&D task. We also show a relationship between the perception of transaction cost and the perceived success of the cooperation. The analysis sheds light on various determinants of transaction costs.
