TY  - JOUR
T1  - A New Graph-Theoretic Heuristic for Facility Layout
AU  - Leung, Janny
Y1  - 1992/04/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.38.4.594
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.38.4.594
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 594
EP  - 605
VL  - 38
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The facility layout problem is important in the modern manufacturing environment because increased machine flexibility and product diversification create additional complexities in scheduling and material handling. An important first step in facility layout is the determination of which machines should be adjacent. This problem can be modelled as that of finding a maximum weight planar subgraph of a graph, given a measure of the desirability that two machines be adjacent based on the anticipated flows and technological constraints. We present a new heuristic that is a generalization of previous work of Foulds and Robinson. Preliminary computational results are presented which suggest that this heuristic performs well.
AB  - The facility layout problem is important in the modern manufacturing environment because increased machine flexibility and product diversification create additional complexities in scheduling and material handling. An important first step in facility layout is the determination of which machines should be adjacent. This problem can be modelled as that of finding a maximum weight planar subgraph of a graph, given a measure of the desirability that two machines be adjacent based on the anticipated flows and technological constraints. We present a new heuristic that is a generalization of previous work of Foulds and Robinson. Preliminary computational results are presented which suggest that this heuristic performs well.
